1
00:01:23,942 --> 00:01:26,534
So nice of you to let me drop
you at your hotel, Mr Darricott.

2
00:01:27,135 --> 00:01:30,318
Of course it's wretched for that exhibit
to be held so near the Metropole.

3
00:01:30,822 --> 00:01:33,001
Or we could have had a longer talk.

4
00:01:34,219 --> 00:01:36,206
I am told that mountains
can be moved by faith.

5
00:01:37,153 --> 00:01:39,665
But I'm afraid that nothing can be
done about moving The Metropole.

6
00:01:40,997 --> 00:01:43,271
However, I console myself.
We meet again in two hours.

7
00:01:43,643 --> 00:01:47,094
I'm so glad you were able to arrange
your engagements so you could come.

8
00:01:47,428 --> 00:01:49,066
We dine early: 7:30.

9
00:01:49,494 --> 00:01:52,212
After all, we must hear
something of the opera.

10
00:01:52,531 --> 00:01:53,342
Ah, yes.

11
00:01:53,878 --> 00:01:57,447
It might be interesting sometime to find
out if Tosca really had a first act.

12
00:02:05,079 --> 00:02:06,864
Good afternoon, Mr Darricott.
- Charles.

13
00:02:09,585 --> 00:02:11,223
Until tonight?
- Until tonight.

14
00:02:23,380 --> 00:02:26,113
"Calling Mr Mellner. 714."

15
00:02:27,379 --> 00:02:28,407
"Mr Mellner."

16
00:02:32,627 --> 00:02:33,904
Here you are, Mr Darricott.

17
00:02:48,719 --> 00:02:50,334
Thank you, Mr Darricott.

18
00:02:51,672 --> 00:02:52,945
Here you are, Mr Darricott.

19
00:02:53,539 --> 00:02:55,041
What a marvelous day, Mr Darricott.

20
00:03:00,544 --> 00:03:04,045
You wouldn't think a fellow could run
up a bill of $28 on 3-cent newspapers.

21
00:03:04,233 --> 00:03:05,022
Would you?

22
00:03:05,210 --> 00:03:08,112
Why not? He ran up $40 on
me on 20-cent cigarettes.

23
00:03:08,471 --> 00:03:09,744
You ain't worried, are you?

24
00:03:09,969 --> 00:03:12,614
No. There's no chance in the world
of that fellow not coming through.

25
00:03:12,901 --> 00:03:13,745
You said it.

26
00:03:14,016 --> 00:03:15,661
They don't make them any nicer than him.

27
00:03:15,952 --> 00:03:17,446
A real swell, is what I mean.

28
00:03:22,637 --> 00:03:24,625
Thank you, Fred.
- Always a pleasure, Mr Darricott.

29
00:03:45,212 --> 00:03:45,913
Eugene.

30
00:03:49,069 --> 00:03:50,216
How do I stand today?

31
00:03:50,726 --> 00:03:53,151
Sorry, Mr Darricott.
You just dropped three million.

32
00:03:54,217 --> 00:03:55,776
Three million, huh?
- Three million.

33
00:03:57,911 --> 00:04:00,246
I'm afraid I haven't the cash
on hand to reimburse you.

34
00:04:01,286 --> 00:04:03,879
Shall we call it square if I let
you read the sporting page first?

35
00:04:04,360 --> 00:04:06,331
Anything you say, Mr Darricott.

36
00:04:07,155 --> 00:04:09,331
I took the other dress
shirt to the laundry.

37
00:04:10,238 --> 00:04:11,294
Thanks, Eugene.

38
00:04:12,429 --> 00:04:14,217
Nice of you to go to so
much trouble for me.

39
00:04:14,942 --> 00:04:17,904
I'd rather do a little valet
service for you for nothing.

40
00:04:18,752 --> 00:04:19,629
Nothing?

41
00:04:20,095 --> 00:04:23,085
Than for some of those guys
who give me 20-dollar tips.

42
00:04:24,024 --> 00:04:26,507
It's not everyone who can have an
address like the Hotel Metropole.

43
00:04:26,695 --> 00:04:28,682
And valet service for
ten dollars a week.

44
00:04:31,162 --> 00:04:33,669
We know a gentleman when
we see one, Mr Darricott.

45
00:04:34,631 --> 00:04:36,074
Stop Eugene. You turn my head.

46
00:04:36,408 --> 00:04:38,339
Shall I lay out the evening
clothes for you, sir?

47
00:04:40,115 --> 00:04:40,730
Yes.

48
00:04:42,566 --> 00:04:44,068
In the meantime, I'll draw my bath.

49
00:04:44,491 --> 00:04:46,451
That is, unless someone
is using it at the moment.

50
00:04:54,869 --> 00:04:56,706
So nice of you to dine
with us, Mr Darricott.

51
00:04:56,894 --> 00:04:58,884
I know how rushed you must be.
- Rushed?

52
00:04:59,361 --> 00:05:02,092
I should think an attractive bachelor
in New York would be stampeded.

53
00:05:02,831 --> 00:05:05,516
How does one avoid being trampled
in the jam, Mr Darricott?

54
00:05:06,206 --> 00:05:08,040
I am afraid I cannot
give expert testimony.

55
00:05:09,016 --> 00:05:10,425
I'm just an innocent bystander.

56
00:05:10,866 --> 00:05:12,159
Innocent bystander?

57
00:05:13,077 --> 00:05:15,533
Isn't that the fellow who always
gets shot by accident?

58
00:05:16,058 --> 00:05:17,109
Why, Peyton.

59
00:05:17,448 --> 00:05:19,957
Don't you ever got shot by
accident, Mr Darricott?

60
00:05:20,977 --> 00:05:22,168
It is so unromantic.

61
00:05:22,555 --> 00:05:25,900
Perhaps you could suggest a romantic
way for Mr Darricott to get shot?

62
00:05:27,139 --> 00:05:30,212
Well. In a pinch I might
shoot him myself.

63
00:05:30,657 --> 00:05:32,502
It would be a pleasure
to be a target for you.

64
00:05:32,690 --> 00:05:34,602
I'd tremble. So I'd probably miss you.

65
00:05:35,562 --> 00:05:36,206
Well.

66
00:05:37,224 --> 00:05:40,110
If you're not going to shoot
Mr Darricott at this very moment ..

67
00:05:40,504 --> 00:05:44,420
It might be fun to see if we can get to
the Robinsons on time just this once.

68
00:05:46,953 --> 00:05:48,340
You'd better hurry too, mother.

69
00:05:48,528 --> 00:05:50,340
You're more than
fashionably late right now.

70
00:05:50,966 --> 00:05:54,642
If we could ever get your father to stop
imitating a caged lion, we can leave.

71
00:05:55,393 --> 00:05:56,494
Horace.
- Yes, dear?

72
00:05:56,765 --> 00:05:58,353
Mr Helden and Mr Dorset are here, sir.

73
00:05:58,593 --> 00:05:59,389
Oh yes.

74
00:05:59,795 --> 00:06:02,138
I am sorry, dear. I had hoped
these fellows wouldn't turn up.

75
00:06:03,088 --> 00:06:06,535
Tony, it looks as if you and I must tear
ourselves away from this nice gathering.

76
00:06:07,080 --> 00:06:08,639
They're here about the Austrian loan.

77
00:06:08,827 --> 00:06:09,928
Horace.
- Yes, dear?

78
00:06:10,373 --> 00:06:14,037
I suppose this means you're not going
to the opera with me again. Is that it?

79
00:06:14,550 --> 00:06:15,382
Afraid so.

80
00:06:15,570 --> 00:06:17,488
The second time this week
you disappoint me.

81
00:06:17,676 --> 00:06:19,457
When I had my heart set on the opera.

82
00:06:19,797 --> 00:06:21,051
Horace.
- I am sorry.

83
00:06:21,385 --> 00:06:23,196
What good does it do
me for you to be sorry?

84
00:06:23,460 --> 00:06:26,008
Night after night if I want to go
anyplace I have to go without you.

85
00:06:26,402 --> 00:06:28,412
It's humiliating.
- Look here, my dear.

86
00:06:28,684 --> 00:06:31,358
It's not as if I didn't want to go.
- I do not believe you.

87
00:06:31,865 --> 00:06:35,005
Well. If we could perhaps
discuss this at another time.

88
00:06:35,321 --> 00:06:37,224
But it's always some other time.

89
00:06:37,562 --> 00:06:38,526
I'm sick of it.

90
00:06:38,819 --> 00:06:41,036
I want to go to the opera and
I want to go with my husband.

91
00:06:41,224 --> 00:06:42,559
You've no right ..
- Mother.

92
00:06:42,747 --> 00:06:46,136
And you. Why must you go to those stupid
business meetings with your father?

93
00:06:46,423 --> 00:06:48,206
If Tony has to go into my bank ..

94
00:06:48,394 --> 00:06:51,935
I don't quite see how he will get along
if he doesn't know something of my work.

95
00:06:53,325 --> 00:06:54,255
Now, goodnight.

96
00:06:54,761 --> 00:06:56,091
Run along, son.
- Goodnight.

97
00:06:56,450 --> 00:06:57,237
Goodnight.

98
00:06:58,212 --> 00:07:01,261
There's one thing you must admit
about our family, Mr Darricott.

99
00:07:01,588 --> 00:07:03,213
Never a dull moment.

100
00:07:05,579 --> 00:07:07,239
Well, if you will excuse me.

101
00:07:07,582 --> 00:07:10,034
Oh, Mr Darricott.
You won't disappoint me, will you?

102
00:07:10,381 --> 00:07:12,298
I've had my heart set on
tonight's performance.

103
00:07:12,557 --> 00:07:14,782
You will like it, you know.
- I shall be delighted.

104
00:07:15,152 --> 00:07:17,868
If Peyton and I didn't have this
engagement we simply must keep ..

105
00:07:18,232 --> 00:07:20,642
I wouldn't think of making you
change your plans, darling.

106
00:07:21,025 --> 00:07:23,518
We have to get to the Robinsons.
- Alright. Alright.

107
00:07:24,279 --> 00:07:25,757
Have a good time, Mr Darricott.

108
00:07:26,245 --> 00:07:27,261
Goodnight, mother.

109
00:07:27,738 --> 00:07:28,525
Goodnight.

110
00:07:35,782 --> 00:07:38,092
It seemed as if you weren't
going to have any choice.

111
00:07:39,187 --> 00:07:40,062
Any choice?

112
00:07:40,575 --> 00:07:42,515
Well, the way things have turned out.

113
00:07:43,622 --> 00:07:46,208
I'm afraid you're going to
have me on your hands ..

114
00:07:46,952 --> 00:07:47,796
For tonight.

115
00:07:48,917 --> 00:07:49,724
At least.

116
00:07:52,422 --> 00:07:53,552
I shall be very happy.

117
00:07:57,420 --> 00:07:58,469
I'll get my wrap.

118
00:08:32,360 --> 00:08:33,393
Lovely, isn't it?

119
00:08:34,567 --> 00:08:35,467
Ah yes.

120
00:08:36,720 --> 00:08:38,022
One of my favorite subjects.

121
00:08:38,980 --> 00:08:39,768
Potemkin?

122
00:08:41,530 --> 00:08:42,729
Catherine and Potemkin.

123
00:08:43,497 --> 00:08:44,083
Oh.

124
00:08:44,953 --> 00:08:45,825
A lucky chap.

125
00:08:46,684 --> 00:08:48,267
That he found his Catherine.

126
00:08:48,950 --> 00:08:49,908
Almost too late.

127
00:08:50,385 --> 00:08:52,798
It would have been rather
tragic for her too, wouldn't it?

128
00:08:53,312 --> 00:08:55,243
If she had not found him.

129
00:08:55,919 --> 00:08:56,711
I wonder.

130
00:08:57,734 --> 00:08:59,293
She made him a great man, didn't she?

131
00:08:59,622 --> 00:09:00,928
He made her a happy woman.

132
00:09:02,106 --> 00:09:03,635
And what better can any man ask for?

133
00:09:04,693 --> 00:09:06,275
If he finds his Catherine.

134
00:09:07,158 --> 00:09:08,393
But a woman can ..

135
00:09:10,145 --> 00:09:12,493
But Catherine did find her Potemkin.

136
00:09:15,277 --> 00:09:16,293
But he had to die.

137
00:09:16,887 --> 00:09:19,222
Does Potemkin always have to die?

138
00:09:20,471 --> 00:09:22,063
What a dreadful fate.

139
00:09:23,786 --> 00:09:24,916
What a glorious death.

140
00:09:28,478 --> 00:09:29,322
Shall we go?

141
00:09:31,291 --> 00:09:32,184
To the ..

142
00:09:33,098 --> 00:09:33,770
Opera?

143
00:09:36,906 --> 00:09:37,778
To the opera.

144
00:09:43,515 --> 00:09:45,486
You are not very
complimentary, Mr Darricott.

145
00:09:46,422 --> 00:09:49,730
I am with you and yet it seems
as though you are alone.

146
00:09:53,716 --> 00:09:54,870
I am always alone.

147
00:09:58,097 --> 00:10:01,256
If you could only know what an evening
like this can mean to a man like me.

148
00:10:02,602 --> 00:10:03,306
A home.

149
00:10:03,855 --> 00:10:04,718
A fireside.

150
00:10:05,338 --> 00:10:06,325
A charming woman.

151
00:10:07,176 --> 00:10:08,717
What good are all those things ..

152
00:10:09,905 --> 00:10:11,137
Where there is no love?

153
00:10:13,192 --> 00:10:14,436
But where there is love ..

154
00:10:16,689 --> 00:10:19,381
I want so badly to talk to you Jamie.

155
00:10:21,728 --> 00:10:23,604
Almost too late for the opera.

156
00:10:25,125 --> 00:10:26,234
It is too late.

157
00:10:26,924 --> 00:10:28,783
It all seems so unimportant.

158
00:10:29,498 --> 00:10:31,675
The opera. Tosca. All those people.

159
00:10:32,689 --> 00:10:34,338
If only we could sit and talk.

160
00:10:36,796 --> 00:10:38,307
Perhaps if we could go to your ..

161
00:10:39,739 --> 00:10:40,410
Well.

162
00:10:40,806 --> 00:10:42,476
Perhaps at The Metropole ..?

163
00:10:44,463 --> 00:10:45,477
Well, if I ..

164
00:10:47,134 --> 00:10:48,454
If I had only known. But ..

165
00:10:48,772 --> 00:10:50,181
Unfortunately, my ..

166
00:10:50,692 --> 00:10:52,548
My rooms are not my
own for this evening.

167
00:10:53,757 --> 00:10:54,751
An old friend.

168
00:10:55,836 --> 00:10:57,854
I know a place where we can be alone.

169
00:11:01,389 --> 00:11:03,203
And that's why I am so unhappy, Jamie.

170
00:11:07,996 --> 00:11:09,054
I am so sorry.

171
00:11:11,641 --> 00:11:13,635
If I could believe you
really meant that.

172
00:11:15,962 --> 00:11:16,981
Please believe it.

173
00:11:17,825 --> 00:11:18,756
Please mean it.

174
00:11:20,609 --> 00:11:21,555
I mean it.

175
00:11:22,845 --> 00:11:23,861
Then I believe it.

176
00:11:25,173 --> 00:11:26,821
How lucky I am.

177
00:11:28,540 --> 00:11:29,212
Lucky?

178
00:11:30,101 --> 00:11:31,231
Lucky to have met you.

179
00:11:32,635 --> 00:11:34,508
I have a husband whose
life is not my life.

180
00:11:35,202 --> 00:11:36,933
I have children whose
lives are their own.

181
00:11:37,358 --> 00:11:38,402
They don't need me.

182
00:11:40,175 --> 00:11:41,009
I need ..

183
00:11:42,854 --> 00:11:43,624
Someone.

184
00:11:44,967 --> 00:11:46,488
I had nothing at all until ..

185
00:11:49,392 --> 00:11:50,241
Until?

186
00:11:51,114 --> 00:11:52,460
Until I met you.

187
00:11:54,347 --> 00:11:55,405
And now ..

188
00:12:09,879 --> 00:12:11,181
Five thousand, Mr Darricott?

189
00:12:12,667 --> 00:12:14,085
Six.
- That's a lot of money.

190
00:12:15,145 --> 00:12:16,304
It's a lot of bracelet.

191
00:12:17,013 --> 00:12:18,070
Okay, Mr Darricott.

192
00:12:18,524 --> 00:12:20,026
I will mail you the check as usual.

193
00:12:20,313 --> 00:12:22,235
Thank you. Good day.
- Good day, sir.

194
00:12:22,761 --> 00:12:23,588
Thank you.

195
00:12:33,657 --> 00:12:35,640
Let's take a look at
those bracelets, Fred.

196
00:12:35,953 --> 00:12:37,925
Alright. But you don't have
to worry about them.

197
00:12:38,244 --> 00:12:39,574
He didn't have to steal them.

198
00:12:40,564 --> 00:12:42,669
That dame is only too glad
to give them to him.

199
00:12:43,139 --> 00:12:43,959
What dame?

200
00:12:44,147 --> 00:12:47,034
Say, I had this out with
headquarters six months ago.

201
00:12:47,473 --> 00:12:49,236
The first time he brought anything in.

202
00:12:50,102 --> 00:12:53,354
Mr Horace Fendley might not know
that these things are missing.

203
00:12:53,777 --> 00:12:55,138
But Mrs Fendley does.

204
00:12:56,288 --> 00:12:59,212
You'll never get a report on
them as stolen property.

205
00:13:00,752 --> 00:13:01,560
Okay.

206
00:13:02,521 --> 00:13:06,597
Gadgets like these convert into cash
with much less trouble than a check.

207
00:13:07,839 --> 00:13:10,442
You have to sign your name on
the back of a check, you know.

208
00:13:24,700 --> 00:13:25,935
I'm sorry, Mr Darricott.

209
00:13:26,206 --> 00:13:27,794
Mrs Fendley left her home an hour ago.

210
00:13:28,093 --> 00:13:29,595
Her maid said there was no message.

211
00:13:31,571 --> 00:13:32,730
Thank you.
- Yes, sir.

212
00:13:33,822 --> 00:13:35,296
And a demitasse?

213
00:13:36,740 --> 00:13:38,362
Well, I think we'd better wait, Victor.

214
00:13:38,607 --> 00:13:39,527
Hello Jamie.

215
00:13:45,318 --> 00:13:45,962
Well.

216
00:13:47,404 --> 00:13:48,076
Hello.

217
00:13:48,652 --> 00:13:49,869
Surprised to see me?

218
00:13:51,036 --> 00:13:51,651
Yes.

219
00:13:52,297 --> 00:13:52,998
And no.

220
00:13:53,358 --> 00:13:55,375
There's a simple explanation
if you care to hear it.

221
00:13:55,666 --> 00:13:58,854
Auntie Mabel decided an hour ago
to enjoy very, very bad health.

222
00:13:59,297 --> 00:14:01,486
So mother had to drive out
to Long Island to see her.

223
00:14:02,300 --> 00:14:05,084
She asked me to phone you and say she
couldn't keep her engagement with you.

224
00:14:05,793 --> 00:14:06,945
But somehow I forgot.

225
00:14:07,827 --> 00:14:09,820
But you remembered to keep
her engagement for her?

226
00:14:10,317 --> 00:14:12,824
As a matter of fact, mother
thought it would be a good idea.

227
00:14:13,476 --> 00:14:14,205
That is.

228
00:14:14,393 --> 00:14:17,660
I'm sure she would have thought it
a good idea if she had thought of it.

229
00:14:18,327 --> 00:14:19,972
Funny. I was about to suggest it myself.

230
00:14:20,295 --> 00:14:21,053
You liar.

231
00:14:21,661 --> 00:14:24,537
What you really mean is you're afraid
you've a wasted evening on your hands.

232
00:14:25,068 --> 00:14:27,323
An evening can never be
called wasted until it's over.

233
00:14:28,485 --> 00:14:30,914
I went to a lot of pains
to dress the part, Jamie.

234
00:14:31,234 --> 00:14:33,110
You won't have to be very ashamed of me.

235
00:14:34,492 --> 00:14:37,529
'Banker's daughter takes world altitude
record reaching for compliments'.

236
00:14:37,913 --> 00:14:39,842
Banker's daughter has
just that intention.

237
00:14:40,174 --> 00:14:42,577
I'm ashamed of you, my dear Rachel.
You are positively ..

238
00:14:42,933 --> 00:14:43,720
Beautiful?

239
00:14:44,126 --> 00:14:45,199
Beautiful of course.

240
00:14:45,761 --> 00:14:47,849
But the word I mean
should also convey ..

241
00:14:48,346 --> 00:14:49,161
Brilliance?

242
00:14:49,674 --> 00:14:50,432
Radiance?

243
00:14:51,494 --> 00:14:54,459
I am sure you know the word I mean.
You're just too modest to use it.

244
00:14:55,525 --> 00:14:57,031
When you call me modest.

245
00:14:57,613 --> 00:14:58,289
Smile.

246
00:14:59,077 --> 00:15:01,540
To call you modest, my dear,
takes more than a smile.

247
00:15:02,728 --> 00:15:03,777
Have it your way.

248
00:15:04,182 --> 00:15:04,826
Well.

249
00:15:05,268 --> 00:15:06,954
Do we dine or do we dine?

250
00:15:09,080 --> 00:15:09,864
We dine.

251
00:15:15,123 --> 00:15:17,017
We'll be two for dinner after all.

252
00:15:17,520 --> 00:15:19,749
Yes, sir. I have the table ready, sir.

253
00:15:21,192 --> 00:15:21,979
Thank you.

254
00:15:22,864 --> 00:15:24,895
Forgive me if I seem too bold.

255
00:15:25,262 --> 00:15:28,869
But dinner and the theater will be just
the hors d'oeuvres of the evening?

256
00:15:30,111 --> 00:15:32,295
And if I might make one more suggestion.

257
00:15:33,109 --> 00:15:36,608
Don't you think it's a good idea if we
kept the rest of the menu to ourselves?

258
00:15:38,661 --> 00:15:39,705
You mean ..

259
00:15:40,099 --> 00:15:41,987
Not to tell ..
- Bright child.

260
00:15:43,592 --> 00:15:45,250
And now, Mr Jamie Darricott.

261
00:15:46,189 --> 00:15:50,290
Suppose I tell you I've looked forward
to substituting for mother for months?

262
00:15:51,848 --> 00:15:53,534
And suppose I tell you ..
- What?

263
00:15:55,017 --> 00:15:56,396
That you are a funny kid.

264
00:15:56,891 --> 00:15:59,125
You'll change your mind about that too.

265
00:16:15,240 --> 00:16:17,238
There you are, Charles.
- Thank you, Mr Darricott.

266
00:16:38,794 --> 00:16:39,677
Mr Darricott.

267
00:16:40,164 --> 00:16:41,981
Your cigarettes got in
today from Cairo, sir.

268
00:16:42,593 --> 00:16:45,071
